To a system equipped with a magnetic stirrer at ambient temperature were added 4-methyl-benzene-1,4-diamine (1a: 0.035 g, 0.28 mmol) in acetic acid (3 mL) and 2‑hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone (2: 0.050 g; 0.28 mmol). The precipitates were separated with filtration after 24 h and washed with H2O (6 mL) to eliminate acid residue. Yield: 0.045 g (60 %), m.p. 275 °C (dec), yellow powder (
                        Scheme 1

                        ) [25].

To a system equipped with a magnetic stirrer at ambient temperature, were added 4-nitro-1,2-phenylenediamine (1b: 0.044 g, 0.28 mmol) in acetic acid (3 mL) and 2‑hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone (2: 0.050 g; 0.28 mmol). The precipitates were separated with filtration after 24 h and washed with H2O (6 mL) to eliminate acid residue. Yield: 0.076 g (91 %), m.p. 280 °C (dec), orange powder (
                        Scheme 1
                        ) [25].

To a system equipped with a magnetic stirrer at ambient temperature were added 3,4-diamino benzophenone (1c: 0.061 g, 0.28 mmol) in acetic acid (3 mL) and 2‑hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone (2: 0.050 g; 0.28 mmol). The precipitates were separated with filtration after 24 h and washed with H2O (6 mL) to eliminate acid residue. Yield: 0.085 g (85 %), m.p. 277 °C (dec), orange powder (
                        Scheme 1
                        ) [25].

To a system equipped with a magnetic stirrer at ambient temperature were added o-phenylene-diamine (1d: 0.031 g; 0.28 mmol) in acetic acid (3 mL) and 2‑hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone (2: 0.050 g; 0.28 mmol). The precipitates were separated with filtration after 24 h and washed with H2O (6 mL) to eliminate acid residue. Yield: 0.064 g (90 %), m.p. 292 °C (dec), orange powder (
                        Scheme 1
                        ) [25].

To a system equipped with a magnetic stirrer at ambient temperature were added diaminomaleonitrile (1e: 0.031 g; 0.28 mmol) in acetic acid (3 mL) and 2‑hydroxy-1,4-naphthoquinone (2: 0.050 g; 0.28 mmol). The precipitates were separated with filtration after 24 h and washed with H2O (6 mL) to eliminate acid residue. Yield: 0.055 g (77 %), m.p. 240 °C (dec), light brown powder (
                        Scheme 1
                        ) [25].

The NCQD was obtained from the pyrolysis of a cheap carbon source. The citric acid (4.00 g) and ammonia (1.00 g) were mixed in distilled water (10 mL) for 30 min with magnetic stirring. Then, in a muffle furnace operating at 10 °C per minute, the solution was heated to 200 °C by heating the air. In the next step, the final product, after cooling, is mixed with acetone under ultrasonic waves. The supernatants containing NCQDs were collected after centrifugation at 10,000 rpm for 15 min. Finally, NCQDs were obtained after the rotational evaporation of supernatant floating particles. The final product was stored as a brown powder at 4 °C (
                        Scheme 2

                        ) [16].

Choline chloride (ChCl) and urea (HBD) were employed in a 1:1 molar ratio to prepare deep eutectic solvents (DESs). Under magnetic stirring, 0.15 g of urea and 0.34 g of ChCl were heated to 100 °C until a colorless and homogeneous liquid appeared. An aqueous solution of citric acid (0.23 g in 12 mL of deionized water) was added to the deep eutectic solvent under magnetic stirring till no solid object was visible. Then, the obtained mixture was heated in an autoclave for 8 h at a temperature of 180 °C. Large particles were eliminated using a centrifuge at 10,000 rpm for 15 min after the autoclave had cooled, and the supernatant was collected. The mixture was filtered with a 0.22 μm filter to eliminate the large particles. The final solution was dialyzed using a 1000 Da dialysis membrane and deionized water for 24 h to remove the reactants that did not participate in the reaction. The resulting N, Cl-CQD powder is black in color and stored at 4 °C (
                        Scheme 3

                        ) [23].
